50|$|There was {{worldwide}} {{shock at}} the huge loss {{of life and the}} procedural errors that had led to it. Public inquiries in Britain and the United States led to major improvements in maritime safety. One of their most important legacies was the establishment in 1914 of the International Convention for the Safety of Life at Sea (SOLAS), which still governs maritime safety today. Additionally, several new wireless regulations were passed around the world in an effort to learn from the many missteps in wireless communicationsâ€”which could have saved many more passengers.Primary to these improved regulations were the installation of radio equipment on ALL ships, fixed <b>Distress</b> <b>frequencies</b> and 24-hour watch on those frequencies.|$|R
